<p class="">The hon. Member ought not to abuse the courtesy afforded him by my giving way, because all he did was to adduce a perfectly irrelevant argument. I am dealing, not with what the local authorities will do, but with what the Minister has done. What he has done is to base his subsidy figure on a standard of housing to which he thinks local authorities ought to build. He jeered at my right hon. Friend the Member for Bishop Auckland (Mr. Dalton) and said that my right hon. Friend had started these houses. But my right hon. Friend never at any time put <span id="262" class="column-number" data-column-number="262"></span> the financial compulsion on local authorities to build them. That is what the right hon. Gentleman has done. He has said, "I will base my subsidies on a sub-standard house"—[HON. MEMBERS: "No "]—of course he did.</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
